<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-07-06T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-07-06T05:00:00-05:00" n="31" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d31">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">600.939/201: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-07-06T19:00:00+09:00">July 6, 1938—7
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received July 6—8:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>444. Tientsin’s 114, July 1, 6 p.m.;<note n="39" xml:id="d31fn39">Not
                                printed.</note> and Department’s 329 [<hi rend="italic">229</hi>],
                            July 2, 7 p.m.,<note n="40" xml:id="d31fn40">See <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note> export embargo hides and skins. I presented
                            this case to the Minister for Foreign Affairs<note n="41" xml:id="d31fn41">Gen. Kazushige Ugaki.</note> during the course of
                            my recent interview with him<note n="42" xml:id="d31fn42">See memorandum
                                of July 4 by the Ambassador in Japan, <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_605"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                        Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 605</ref>, <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_610">610</ref>.</note> (our 437, July 4, 7 p.m.<note n="43" xml:id="d31fn43">See telegram No. 945, July 5, noon, from the Consul
                                General at Shanghai, <ref target="frus1938v03#pg_211">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 211</ref>.</note>) and today
                            we delivered to the Foreign Office an <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> along the lines desired by the Department.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Peiping for Tientsin and Hankow.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>